95
00:06:14,630 --> 00:06:19,640
Who would consider the great events that marked the 15th and 16th century.

96
00:06:19,640 --> 00:06:21,920
Changes in military technology.

97
00:06:21,920 --> 00:06:26,630
Also, the question of politics or religion during this period.

98
00:06:26,630 --> 00:06:28,820
The influence of the papacy.

99
00:06:28,820 --> 00:06:34,940
The rise of ducal states and their sense of an autonomy from the papacy.

100
00:06:34,940 --> 00:06:39,590
All of these are left out of Wittkower's narrative.

101
00:06:39,590 --> 00:06:45,470
To read Wittkower is to see a process of mental abstraction at work.

102
00:06:45,470 --> 00:06:48,560
In other words, what Wittkower was after wasn't

103
00:06:48,560 --> 00:06:52,370
the discrete cultural meaning of a particular building

104
00:06:52,370 --> 00:06:54,000
in a particular context.

105
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:58,760
He's not after giving us some real and robust sense of the 16th century world

106
00:06:58,760 --> 00:06:59,900
view.

107
00:06:59,900 --> 00:07:04,910
Instead, he wants to bring together the classical kit of parts

108
00:07:04,910 --> 00:07:07,880
that make a building formalize itself, that

109
00:07:07,880 --> 00:07:12,680
allow it to transform into the buildings we still have today.

110
00:07:12,680 --> 00:07:16,310
In other words, Wittkower is looking for a kind of deep structure,

111
00:07:16,310 --> 00:07:20,660
we might call it, that organizes architectural form.

112
00:07:20,660 --> 00:07:24,230
He's going after the identification of their component parts.

113
00:07:24,230 --> 00:07:25,310
What is a portico?

114
00:07:25,310 --> 00:07:26,510
What is a column?

115
00:07:26,510 --> 00:07:32,510
This is why ultimately, he relies on diagrams to explain architecture.

116
00:07:32,510 --> 00:07:36,050
He looks through the complex appearance of a building like this

117
00:07:36,050 --> 00:07:39,050
in all its three-dimensionality and distills it

118
00:07:39,050 --> 00:07:44,300
into its most basic elements through plan, sometimes elevation.

119
00:07:44,300 --> 00:07:48,470
In other words, he develops a syntax, a language, a form.

120
00:07:48,470 --> 00:07:52,190
He's interested in Renaissance architecture as an explicitly--

121
00:07:52,190 --> 00:07:53,540
and these are his words--

122
00:07:53,540 --> 00:07:58,980
as an explicitly "mathematical science which worked with spatial units."

123
00:07:58,980 --> 00:08:01,970
Wittkower's whole analysis along these lines

124
00:08:01,970 --> 00:08:08,000
can be understood as a philosophical exercise, not an historical analysis.

125
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:12,080
In which thinking and reason emerge as the defining

126
00:08:12,080 --> 00:08:15,020
characteristics of the architect.

127
00:08:15,020 --> 00:08:17,810
And this is what's demonstrated through the diagrams.

128
00:08:17,810 --> 00:08:23,370
Ultimately, what emerges from this is the autonomy of architecture itself.

129
00:08:23,370 --> 00:08:28,240
And we see this when we look at what his diagram of the Villa Cornaro does.

130
00:08:28,240 --> 00:08:31,160
You can see that he's interested only in the plan.

131
00:08:31,160 --> 00:08:34,429
He cuts away the rear monumental staircase.

132
00:08:34,429 --> 00:08:40,250
He minimizes and essentially elides the entrance porch, takes away the column,

133
00:08:40,250 --> 00:08:43,789
